"span": {"begin": 1434, "end": 1438}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013438"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "thiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.7104455232620239, "span": {"begin": 1546, "end": 1551}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7296"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "TrxR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9937822818756104, "span": {"begin": 1671, "end": 1675}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:57783"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NADPH", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997549653053284, "span": {"begin": 1679, "end": 1684}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5447"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NADPH-dependent lipid hydroperoxide reductase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9922664761543274, "span": {"begin": 1679, "end": 1724}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29192"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hydroperoxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9980296492576599, "span": {"begin": 1701, "end": 1714}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:57783"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NADPH", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997323155403137, "span": {"begin": 1731, "end": 1736}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2908"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "GR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9579156041145325, "span": {"begin": 1815, "end": 1817}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005978"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GSH", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9619163274765015, "span": {"begin": 1830, "end": 1833}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013438"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "thiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9950650334358215, "span": {"begin": 1877, "end": 1882}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7296"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "TrxR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1945, "end": 1949}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7295"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Trx", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9945060610771179, "span": {"begin": 1987, "end": 1990}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7295"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Trx", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.991367757320404, "span": {"begin": 2004, "end": 2007}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:55829"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "selenoproteins", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9947304725646973, "span": {"begin": 2091, "end": 2105}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:140606"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "SelP, H, K, S, R, and W selenoproteins", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9534094333648682, "span": {"begin": 2115, "end": 2153}}], "text": "High levels reactive oxygen species (ROS) can be very damaging to cells and molecules within the cell.&nbsp; As a result, the cell has important defense mechanisms to protect itself from ROS, such as glutathione and selenoenzymes.  &nbsp;  Glutathione (GSH) is the most abundant low molecular mass thiol compound synthesized in cells, reaching intracellular concentrations of 1&ndash;10 mM, and is the major antioxidant and redox buffer in human cells. In fact, GSH serves as a reducing agent for ROS and other unstable molecules generated by catalytic systems, including glutathione peroxidase (GPx)(Forman, 2009).  &nbsp;  Selenium plays a crucial role in antioxidant defense, as one Se atom is absolutely required at the active site of all selenoenzymes, such as GPx and thioredoxin reductase (TrxR), in the form of selenocystein (Rayman, 2000). GPx is an antioxidant enzyme that, in the presence of tripeptide GSH, adds two electrons to reduce H2O2 and lipid peroxides to water and lipid alcohols, respectively, while simultaneously oxidizing GSH to glutathione disulfide. The GPx/GSH system is thought to be a major defense in low-level oxidative stress, and decreased GPx activity or GSH levels may lead to the absence of adequate H2O2 and lipid peroxides detoxification, which may be converted to OH-radicals and lipid peroxyl radicals, respectively, by transition metals (Fe2+) (Brigelius-Flohe, 2013). Thioredoxin reductase (TrxR) is essential for maintaining intracellular redox status. The expression of this small (12 kDa) ubiquitous thiol-active protein is induced by ROS and an elevated serum level may indicate a state of oxidative stress. In this regard, TrxR, a NADPH-dependent lipid hydroperoxide reductase, uses NADPH to maintain the levels of reduced Trx via a mechanism similar to that used by GR to maintain GSH levels, contributing to the maintenance of thiol redox homeostasis in proteins. Importantly, the inhibition of TrxR impairs the cyclical regeneration of Trx activity, as Trx remains in the oxidized state (Bjornstedt, 1995, Zhong, 2002). Other, less studied selenoproteins, such as SelP, H, K, S, R, and W selenoproteins, play a role in antioxidant defense (Pisoschi, 2015, Reeves, 2009)", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:29:27 +0000 2026"}